Question 2¶

Based on the violin plot there seems to be different distribution for life expectancy depending on the year. Some violin plots can be grouped together for their similarity in distribution. For years between 1950 to 1960, the life Expectancy was skewed towards the higher age meaning majority of countries had a lower than median life expectancy. For years between 1960 to 1975, the distribution seems symmetric around the center. There are about as many countries that have a lower than average life expectancy as there are countries higher than the average during these years. For every year past 1975, the distribution is skewed towards the lower ages meaning that majority of countries had a life expectancy greater than the average. There is a very noticable outlier in the plot, 1992, where one country had a extremely low life expectancy compared to the other countries and even years. This could likely be due to a disease or war that wiped out lots of the population.

Question 3¶

I would reject the null hypothesis based on plot I made. The center of each violin is higher than the year before it. This is a noticable increase in the average life expectancy overtime that it would be surprising if there was no relationship between the two.

Question 4¶

I think a violin plot for the residuals would look pretty similar to the one for life expectancy. If we were to put a linear regression on the previous violin plot then I believe the line would end up close to where the centers of each violin plot. Since the line is close to the centers, if we were to take the residuals of each violin plot then the distribution would stay the same. The sides where there are more countries distributed in the violin plot would still have a higher distribution of countries in the residuals plot.

Question 5¶

The violin plot should have the mean/center of each year's violin be centered at 0. The overall distribution of the violin as in the shape of the violin should have the center be the widest and as you go towards the ends of the violin it will become thinner and thinner. This means, like a bell shape curve, the center has the highest count of residuals and as you head towards both ends the amount of residuals will similarly decrease. This ideal violin plot is created on the assumptoins that residuals are independent from one another, the variance of residuals is constant, and that residuals are normally distributed.

residuals = []

    residuals.append(lifeExp[i] - predictions[i])

Question 9¶

Yes there does seem to be a dependence between residual and continent. It seems that more developed continents like the Americas, Europe, and Oceania have rwsiduals that are overall above 0 meaning they have a greater than predicted life expectancies. The less developed continents Africa and Asia have a majority of residuals at or below 0. This means when performing regression analysis for life expectancy we should do one analysis for each continent instead of all the continents together. The life expectancy regression of Africa will likely be different from Oceania.

Question 12¶

I created a prediction function that takes in a continent where 0 is Africa, 1 Americas, 2 Asia, 3 Europe, & 4 Oceania and a year and returns the predicted life expectancy of that continent in that year. lm.params contains the y-intercepts of each continent in indicies 0 upto len(lm.params/2) - 1 and the coefficients from len(lm.params/2) upto the end of the array.

In [29]:
def predict_life(continent, year):
    return lm.params[continent + int(len(lm.params)/2)] * year + lm.params[continent]

Exercise 7¶

The function below takes in an integer value which represents a continent and a dataframe and returns the predicted life expectancy of every row's year in the dataframe. The continent given is used to see which coefficient from the linear regression will be used to calculate the predicted life expectancy of the given year from the dataframe

In [31]:
def predict_continent(continent, df):
    coef = lm.params[continent + int(len(lm.params)/2)]
    intercept = lm.params[continent]
    prediction = []
    
    for index, row in df.iterrows():
         prediction.append(coef * row['year'] + intercept)
    
    return prediction

I would say that the violins of each plot follows the assumptions of a linear regression model somewhat well. One assumption is the fact that residuals are normally distributed meaning that the center of every violin should be the largest bump and the ends of the violins are equally distant from the center. Looking at the plots, I will say that Africa, Americas, Asia, and Europe's distributions don't quite match up with a normal distribution but it is still pretty close. Another assumption is a linear relationship. The plots do show that there is a linear relationship between year and residual life expectancy, increasing at a constant rate. So the violin plots somewhat follow the assumptions.

Part 2¶

I am using the iris dataset which includes 4 attributes of the sepal width & length and the petals width & length as well as the 3 classification of the iris based off its attributes. My models will try to predict which of the 3 classifications a given iris will be given it's attributes.

I decided to compare the decision tree against the random forest model because random forests simply use multiple decision trees when predicting. I wanted to see whether this use of multiple trees would substantially improve prediction accuracy at a cost of using more resources. When comparing the performance of decision trees vs random forests, I will decide which is better at classification by checking their accuracy and recall. I chose these two metrics because accuracy is an easy to understand gauge of how good a model's predictions are and recall helps show how much of the dataset the model was eventually able to accurately predict.

I first grab the iris dataset then change the [0,1,2] classification of the iris to it's target names [setosa, versicolor, virginica] for readability. Then I perform holdout validation by splittng the data into a 80% training set and a 20% test set. I chose this ratio because it the standard which means that it should've been tested to be a good ratio for accuracy.

ind_train, ind_test, dep_train, dep_test = ms.train_test_split(iris.data, iris_target, test_size = 0.2)

I chose to create a decision tree with a depth of 5 because it seems reasonable when looking at the iris dataset. There are 4 attributes to an iris and with a depth of 5, each level in the decision tree can ask a question about one of the 4 attributes which should allow for an accurate classification of each iris.

In [51]:
dt = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth = 5)
dt = dt.fit(ind_train, dep_train)

I decided to create a random forest madel with 10 decision trees rather than the default 100 because in this scenario there are only 3 possible classifications of iris so anymore than even 5 feels like it would be wasting resources for around the same predictive accuracy.

Accuracy is calculated by taking the number of correct predictions and dividing it by the total number of predictions.

In [55]:
accuracy_rf = accuracy_score(dep_test, predict_rf)
accuracy_dt = accuracy_score(dep_test, predict_dt)
print(f"Decision Tree accuracy:  {accuracy_dt}")
print(f"Random Forests accuracy: {accuracy_rf}")

Decision Tree accuracy:  0.9666666666666667
Random Forests accuracy: 0.9666666666666667

Looking at the recall in this scenario appears to be redundant as it has the same result as accuracy. This is likely because there are 3 classifications of iris instead of 2 and recall works better in binary situations. For this test the recall_score function has the added "average = 'micro'" which counts the total true positives, false negatives and false positives and compares it the correctly predicted positives. This is practically the same as accuracy.

In [56]:
recall_rf = recall_score(dep_test, predict_rf, average = 'micro')
recall_dt = recall_score(dep_test, predict_dt, average = 'micro')

print(f"Decision Tree recall:  {recall_dt}")
print(f"Random Forest recall:  {recall_rf}")

Decision Tree recall:  0.9666666666666667
Random Forest recall:  0.9666666666666667

Each time I reload the project, the accuracy and precision for the decision tree and random forest changes due to the train and test sets being different each time. However one thing that is apparent is that the accuracy and recall of the decision tree model is almost always close to the random forest's. It's possible that the small size of the iris dataset or how there are only 3 classifications of iris affected the results. Maybe random forest's would be more accurate than decision trees in much larger datasets. But for this comparison decision trees seem to be the better of the two because it has very comparable results to the random forest, many times even having higher accuracy & recall, while being less resource intensive since it's just one tree versus random forest's many.
